nsibility and group-based Guilt</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E015646/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project introduces a social psychological analysis of the role of moral responsibility for the consequences of ingroup wrongdoing. Based on philosophical and political writings (eg by Hannah Arendt), this project investigates empirically feelings of moral responsibility in distinction from guilt for the harm committed by other ingroup members. Feelings of moral responsibility and group-based guilt originate from the shared group membership with the perpetrators without being personally responsible for causing the harm. As such both experiences are ?group-based? and analyzed as intergroup phenomena. However, moral responsibility is conceptualized as a more cognitive and non-affective motivation which triggers attitude change and behaviour above and beyond feelings of group-based guilt.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The key findings of a series of nine studies conducted in the field and in the laboratory revealed that moral responsibility independently predicted lower prejudice, behavioural intentions to approach the victims, and greater intentions to help and donate money. Various methodological and statistical approaches including experimental manipulations, structural equation modelling, and regression analyses were used to demonstrate the reliability and strength of these effects. Taken together, the findings highlight that the motivational component previously attributed to group-based guilt can be explained to a large extent by the acceptance of moral responsibility.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-02-28</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>75520</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E015646/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:te